\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2715041 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12131203\charrsid2754318 Oh I rememb
er - yes, I was old enough 'cos I was over - twenty-odd wasn't I - I must have been about twenty-two or twenty-three if not more. See, I was older than -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7222989 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12131203\charrsid2754318 It was quite a long time afterwards?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2715041 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12131203\charrsid2754318 Oh yes. Quite a time. But - he was very kind man to he
r, I don't think she - you know, had it - had so much kindness shown to her really because my step-father was a very - very quick tempered man and he was very jealous of my mother because she was a nice looking woman, she was really, she was a lovely look
ing woman, my mother was. She had beautiful black hair, lovely skin and more - more of a peachy skin, you know. And I think he was rather jealous of her because she did try hard to - to keep the place going and all that kind of thing you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7222989 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12131203\charrsid2754318 He also w
orked at the docks but he worked on the docks - he didn't go to sea much did he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2715041 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12131203\charrsid2754318 
Yes, he went to sea be - yes, he went to sea but he gave it up when he got married to my mother, you see, because he - he was a - a proper shipwright. Shipwright, you kn
ow, he done - he used to work very hard you know, very hard indeed. But of course - the latter years - like after he - he retired he never done anything really Very, very - very little work he done after that you see. And I remember that - we was on hard 
t
ime then when my mother died because I went and got a - see she didn't get her - a pension until he was sixty-five in August. Well she didn't draw that pension a six months. See. Because I drew - I used to go and take it for her as she was always ill in b
e
d. I used to get her pension. And he drew that from the August to the last - Friday - of January. 'Cos I went - I went in - I went down to the Post Office, I got that ten shillings 'cos they didn't have much then and when she died that was every penny she
 
had in her purse underneath her pillow was the ten shillings I got pension, and that's every ha'penny she had because he didn't get much - pension, you see, and that was - well that went - that used to pay the rent you see, 'cos mum always said, well, she
 
said, you can eat and sleep - eat in the street but I cannon sleep in it so that's what she done - always pay the rent. And I always remember him taking it up, my step-father - every Friday morning when he got his pension, he'd take the rent book and take
 it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7222989 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12131203\charrsid2754318 He got ten shillings as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2715041 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12131203\charrsid2754318 
He - he - no - he - how much did - I don't know how much they got - they didn't get a lot anyway not them - them days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7222989 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12131203\charrsid2754318 Did he have other kinds of jobs after he worked on the dock?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2715041 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12131203\charrsid2754318 No, no, it was alwa
ys in the dock whatever he done but I think after mum died he didn't do much.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7222989 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12131203\charrsid2754318 Do you know what sort of things he used to do in the docks?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2715041 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12131203\charrsid2754318 
Well on ships doing cork - corking and all that kind of thing - and all that kind of thing. Yes, repairing 
- doing the ships - what they call corking, I don't know what they mean by that you see. And all that kind of thing sort of. Oh it is complicated really. Yes. Very complicated.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7222989 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12131203\charrsid2754318 Was your mother a Canning Town girl?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2715041 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12131203\charrsid2754318 No, she - oh no, no, she came f
rom Liverpool, mother, she was born in Liverpool. She was Liverpool person, yes. Her mother and - her father was - he was Liverpool and her mother was - a Devonshire person, she come from Davonshire you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7222989 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12131203\charrsid2754318 You said your mother worked?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2715041 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12131203\charrsid2754318 Well, I 
mean, she used to go out to work - do different jobs you see, like - any lady would - would want her 'cos them days the ladies used to be - you know - they used to be glad of help - house - and she'd do housework or she'd do washing or do anything like th
at for half a crown. Half a crown.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7222989 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12131203\charrsid2754318 Would that be for a whole day's work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2715041 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12131203\charrsid2754318 
Yes. A whole day's work. Half a crown, yes. And you'd think you'd got a lot then. Because you could go out and get ha'porth or this and ha'porth of that and - you could go up the road and get twopennyworth of dabs and that and - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12395442\charrsid2754318 six pound}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12131203\charrsid2754318 
 of potatoes or eight pound of potatoes for a penny you know, years ago, could do that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7222989 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12131203\charrsid2754318 So half a crown went quite a long way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2715041 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12131203\charrsid2754318 Oh it did - yes, and you'd get a nice big loaf for a penny }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10642985\charrsid2754318 three farthings}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12131203\charrsid2754318  you see. And butter or margarine whatever it might be.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7222989 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12131203\charrsid2754318 So your mother would get up very early in the morning?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2715041 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12131203\charrsid2754318 
Oh, she would - yes. After - well after - she'd get up in the morning like get us up and wash us and dress us and
 leave us - you know - except them that went to school, well of course I mean I didn't go to school for a long time, you see, and they'd go to school, well then if she got - she come back home she - like as she come home - she come home to dinner to get u
s
 a bit of dinner see, she'd go up the road. She'd get say two faggots for threeha'pence and - and two pound of potatoes or something like that you see and we always had hot dinner some kind. When - when we - when they came home from school - she'd get bon
e
s and - you know, bacon bones or meat bones and stew them and - get some - ha'porth of poy bergs and put in and make proper, you know. She was - she - she - she always - she'd make a little go a long way you know, she was very, very - and - she was a very
 - well very - if she'd had the right man she'd have}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14100789\charrsid2754318  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12131203\charrsid2754318 
had - she'd have been able to make a proper - she'd been a made - made woman you know but she didn't have the right husband you see to help her. She was - doing one thing and he was doing the other you see, so -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7222989 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12131203\charrsid2754318 Do you mean she was a very hard working woman and her husband wasn't so?

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2715041 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12131203\charrsid2754318 
Oh definitely. Definitely. Oh yes, definitely, every - and she used to do ship's washing. She used to - a friend that knew here he - if the ships come in the dock 
he used to come up and he'd say, Mrs Harris, so and so's in. You know, all the stewards coats and the trousers and all that kind of things, well she'd be up 'til three o'clock in the morning washing them and iron them, starching them and iron them and the
n
 she'd put them in a - you know, in their basket and one of my brothers or sisters, they would help her to carry it down to the docks you see, well, I don't know - I suppose she'd get about three or four pound for that. Well that used to - help her quite 
a
 lot then but then again she'd have to wait months and months for another ship coming in you see. So I mean she'd - she'd know what it - she didn't know what it was to work hard you know. She didn't have an easy time but of course when she married my step
-father he - he had a job, he was working in the dock you see and his money wasn't - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4352290\charrsid2754318 wasn\rquote t}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12131203\charrsid2754318  all that much but at least she - she knew she didn't have to worry about getting the next meal for him you see. So - that - I don't know how many years they were mar
ried, I couldn't quite remember. See how old our mum would - he was - he was about forty-six - of course our mum was much older than him, she was turned sixty anyway, you see, and then of course she - they lived quite happily together, they were quite hap
py and he was very, very kind to her you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7222989 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12131203\charrsid2754318 Was he kind to you as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2715041 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12131203\charrsid2754318 
Oh he was wonderfully kind. Well he knows I wouldn't stand any nonsense you see. I - I - I wouldn't stand any nonsense and he knows that - he knew it rather, so - anyway h
e didn't drink or anything. He was very, very respectful in every way. Very, very respectful. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7222989 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12131203\charrsid2754318 You can remember him much more clearly than your own father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2715041 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12131203\charrsid2754318 
I can - yes, I can - I can remember - well I mean you come to think twenty years to look after a man like that and hardly anything coming in.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7222989 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12131203\charrsid2754318 That's what you had?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2715041 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12131203\charrsid2754318 
That's what I had, myself. I mean, nine and six to keep two people on, I think it was - well many a time I never had a penny for the light or anything - I never had a bit of tea or anything else in the place. So you have to go without it you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7222989 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12131203\charrsid2754318 That's why you feel you're well off at the moment?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2715041 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12131203\charrsid2754318 Oh at present, yes, thank God I do, I do. I do.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7222989 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12131203\charrsid2754318 Was your mother very ill for a long time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2715041 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12131203\charrsid2754318 Oh yes, she w
as ill for - for years - a good few years our mother was ill, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7222989 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12131203\charrsid2754318 Where were you living then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2715041 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12131203\charrsid2754318 We lived in Butchers Road then. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7222989 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12131203\charrsid2754318 So did you have to look after your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2715041 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12131203\charrsid2754318 Yes, I had to - I had a six roomed house to keep clean. I h
ad all the washing to do. I had - to go out and get the food and bring it in. And take it up to her '}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4352290\charrsid2754318 cos}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12131203\charrsid2754318  she was in bed. Well not in - and in between that then you see my sister that got married - the one - not next to me but the one next to my brother - s
he got married. Well she had a little girl a year and six months old when her son - when the boys was born. Well he was about - say he was getting on for four and - of course, the father he used - he used to go away to sea - he was a steward at sea and he
 
used to go away for months and never come back well this time he did come back and of course - my mother was very upset about it and - Flo called him - brought him in and made him his tea and all that - of course I had to do all that and he says - she say
s
 to him, now look here, she said, what are you going to do? Because my sister had to go out to work you see - she wouldn't stop at home and go on the Assistance Board. She wouldn't stop at home but she should have stopped at home and looked after them chi
ldren, well I had all that worry of them children.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7222989 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12131203\charrsid2754318 You looked after the children as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2715041 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12131203\charrsid2754318 
I looked after the children - 'til they were fourteen years of age. I mean I had all that worry when they were ill and sick. All of it to do. But anyway sh
e - she couldn't stop at home, no, she couldn't she had to go cut to work. Well, she went. And this day he come - oh - about fourteen months after, you know, so she said - I had to smile - she sent my - sent the little boy in, she said - 'cos he was in th
e
 front room, mum was in the kitchen - so he said - she said to Andrew - go in and ask daddy if he's got sixpence for a loaf for you. So he went in, he said, daddy, nanny says have you got a sixpence for bread for me? So he said, no, he said, sonny, I'm so
rry, he said, I haven't even got sixpence for myself. So, anyway mother said, well make him a cup of tea and give him a bit of egg and baco}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4352290\charrsid2754318 
n and I did. So - he wait}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12131203\charrsid2754318 ed until my - I think she - yes, he waited until my sister came home and then he - well - I d
on't know what happened then, I can't quite know what happened, but he went away and we never see him from that day to this. We don't know where he is or where he went to. Never, And of course he did find out one - - 'cos she used to come home - like she 
u
sed to come home and she was very sick and tired after coming home so mother said, best thing you can do it get a room and - come home at the weekends to help Mary, she said, because that girl can't do everything for you. Well anyway she come home for a f
e
w weekend then she got in with this friend and she was a French girl and of course she sort of - you know - she changed altogether, she wasn't the same. Well when the children got fourteen - the girl wanted to go up with her mother, she didn't want to sto
p
 there so she went up to - her mother said, well pack her up and let her go, she said, you've got enough worry, she said, you're not going to be worried anymore with them. So anyway - and then the boy started, see, 'cos he left school after and he wanted 
-
 so she said, go on - up you go. I'm not standing for anymore of this she said, you've had enough worry - let 'em go. Of course that upset the apple cart of their mother and her friend you see, they didn't like that kind of thing. It was upsetting their p
leasure you see. So anyway that was the end of that you see, and then - then you see, it was a bit quieter for me, I didn't - you now, have all that worry of them and of course - I got -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7222989 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12131203\charrsid2754318 You looked after your mother after that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2715041 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12131203\charrsid2754318 Looked after mothe
r and dad - step-father and done the housework and all that kind of thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7222989 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12131203\charrsid2754318 Did your mother go out to work when she was with your step-father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2715041 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12131203\charrsid2754318 No. No. No, no, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7222989 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12131203\charrsid2754318 She didn't have to work then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2715041 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12131203\charrsid2754318 She didn't - that's what I say, it was so 
- so - different for her you see. No, she didn't have to go out to work then.
