d that. And I remember one - one time that - she was really - hard up and pushed she went to the Assistance Board. And of course she happened to - like she always used to go to a church every Sunday - every morning - week - every morning there used to be 
w
hat they called a ten o'clock mass you know, being a Catholic, and she'd go up to St Margarets every - morning, see, after they went to school and that and - if she had any coppers she'd come through a place called Rathbone - you know Rathbone Street - an
d them days you could get a lovely plate of plaice, you know about six plaice or a - some little pieces of meat you know for about tuppence or threepence and then she'd get som}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14100789\charrsid2754318 e potatoes and all that stuff. Honestly}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12131203\charrsid2754318  - shilling would go more - two days pract
ically than what a pound'll go today. Honest. And then she'd come home, she'd - well she'd put them on a - on a shelf - this day she come home, put them on a shelf, see, she'd been up to the Assistance and asked them if they could help her because she cou
ldn't - carry on anymore.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7222989 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12131203\charrsid2754318 Was this when your father was ill?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2715041 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12131203\charrsid2754318 
When he was ill - when he was ill you see, my dad was ill. And - anyway this chap come down and - she - took the clothes off - off of us and washed them and put them on the line see, to
 air. 'Cos we did have something she put on us anyway. And this fellow come down, you know, he had a stick and he said, oh, he said, you're not destitute, he said, you've got clothes on the line he said, and you've tot a plate of fish and a plate of meat,
 
he said. So she said, yes, she said, you know how much that cost, she said, that cost me fourpence. She said, and I've got a pennyworth of - of - vegetables, she says, to go with it, and I bought a loaf - a pennythree an loaf, 'cos get a nice big loaf a p
e
nny three. Oh, he said, you're not destitute, you'd better come up, he said, to the committee. They were - oh they were beasts them days - absolute beasts they were. So anyway she - she goes up to the - oh she meets a friend, a Mr - gentleman named Mr Fur
l
ong, he used to - you know, he'd known mum and that - he belonged to the church and that and - anyway - he - he met mother so he said, where are you going Mrs Harris, you look very worried She said, well Sir, she said, you know I - she said, my husband's 
b
een out of work she said, with his accident and I've got nothing, she said, he'd lost the case, she said, and the boy's in - missing at sea, because he was missing at sea, my brother. My eldest brother. And - of course - with - what with that worry and on
e
 worry and the other, so anyway he said, where are you going? She said, I'm going up to the Assistance Board, she said, and he - Mr - one of the chaps had been own she said, and of course I had a bit of a twopennyworth of fish on a place and a couple of p
e
nn'roth of - you know - cuttings like of meat and children's clothes which you know I took off and washed. He said, oh, he said, you're not destitute. He said, aren't you see said, well as it happens he said, I'm on that committee this morning Mrs Harris,
 
he said, and I'll pass it. So of course when - when she went in she - he didn't know Mr - this gentleman. Ho, he said, you know, they were horrible - God forgive me, they were horrible - ho, he said, this woman; said that - wanting help he said, she's not
 
destitute, he said, I see a big place of fish on the shelf he said, he said, a plate of meat and a clothes full of children's clothes - so this man said - excuse me, can I speak? So he said, yes certainly. He said, look, he said, I know this lady, he said
,
 and she is in desperate need of help - he said, she's got four children, he said, and a - she's got a crippled daughter. And he said, everywhere she goes that daughter - and she's got to go anywhere she has to carry that child with her. So he said, this 
is a most deserving case, he said, and she wants all you can give her. Well }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4352290\charrsid2754318 s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12131203\charrsid2754318 o you know what they give her? Two loaves. Two loaves of bread for the week and - a ticket for - to get a bit of - of meat and stuff. And he said, don't get cakes with the - with t
he ticket he said. And don't get cakes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7222989 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12131203\charrsid2754318 You can remember this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2715041 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12131203\charrsid2754318 Yes. Our mother. I remember my mother telling me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7222989 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12131203\charrsid2754318 How old were you then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2715041 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12131203\charrsid2754318 
Oh I couldn't tell you how old I was love. Oh I was getting on in years you know,; but not - but 
- no, I should be about - let me see - oh I'd be about ten or - or nine or ten, something like that. And anyway this is how he treated her and every week she had to go up for them two loaves and this ticket - about three and six I think it used to be. The
 said what about - oh, he said, don't know anything about the rent he said, you've got to find that yourself. They never helped in them days. That's what I say today they don't understand.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7222989 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12131203\charrsid2754318 Why were they like this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2715041 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12131203\charrsid2754318 I don't know love - honest to God.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7222989 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12131203\charrsid2754318 Was it just a particularly unpleasant man that came to see you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2715041 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12131203\charrsid2754318 
They were all like it love. They were all like - there was - I don't - I don't - even in my time - I've had to go up there - I've come home - I broke my heart, I have honest -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7222989 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12131203\charrsid2754318 The way you were treated?
